04267nam a22006495i 9780292798151DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212003txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927981517 a10.7560/7527572doi  a(DE-B1597)587020  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aE184.M5 ǂb M3567 2003eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a323.11680731 aMárquez, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConstructing Identities in Mexican-American Political Organizations :bChoosing Issues, Taking Sides /cBenjamin Márquez. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (181 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Mexican-American Organizations and Identity Politics -- t2. Constructing Identities in Mexican-American Social Movement Organizations -- t3. Voces Unidas: The Southwest Network for Environmental and Economic Justice -- t4. Standing for the Whole: The Southwest Industrial Areas Foundation Network -- t5. Aquí Se Habla Dinero: The Texas Association of Mexican American Chambers of Commerce -- t6. One Dream, Many Voices: The Mexican American Women’s National Association -- t7. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe formation of a group identity has always been a major preoccupation of Mexican American political organizations, whether they seek to assimilate into the dominant Anglo society or to remain separate from it. Yet organizations that sought to represent a broad cross section of the Mexican American population, such as LULAC and the American G.I. Forum, have dwindled in membership and influence, while newer, more targeted political organizations are prospering—clearly suggesting that successful political organizing requires more than shared ethnicity and the experience of discrimination. This book sheds new light on the process of political identity formation through a study of the identity politics practiced by four major Mexican American political organizations—the Southwest Network for Environmental and Economic Justice, the Southwest Industrial Areas Foundation, the Texas Association of Mexican American Chambers of Commerce, and the Mexican American Women's National Association (now known as MANA—A National Latina Organization). Through interviews with activists in each organization and research into their records, Benjamin Marquez clarifies the racial, class-based, and cultural factors that have caused these organizations to create widely differing political identities. He likewise demonstrates why their specific goals resonate only with particular segments of the Mexican American community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aMexican AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aMexican AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aMexican AmericansxSocieties, etc. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75275740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798151423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798151/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK